Title:
Decondition Enumerator

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post continues prior work on “deconditioning” detections by probing how an EDR/AV “Process Identification” (PI) cache behaves when a process is marked detected/known-bad versus “cutoff/deconditioned.”  
- It reports an observed cooldown/reset window for the cache of roughly 5–15 minutes after a PI reaches a detected or cutoff state.  
- The author describes a test methodology: create two near-identical binaries (A.exe and A’.exe) with a single controlled difference, run A to trigger detection, then run A’ with deconditioning to infer whether both map to the same PI.  
- Initial results suggest PI is not based on superficial attributes like filename, compile timestamp, or common similarity/fingerprinting metrics (imphash, SSDeep, TLSH), since changing these did not alter PI.  
- The post links to a set of tested executables (LsassReader variants) used to reproduce the experiments.  
- It’s mainly useful for red teamers and malware/tool developers trying to understand what features drive process identity and caching in detection pipelines.

Technical Focus:
- EDR/AV process identity (PI) and caching behavior
- Deconditioning/cutoff mechanics and cooldown timing
- Differential binary testing (single-variable changes)
- Static similarity/fingerprinting metrics (imphash, SSDeep, TLSH)
- Detection state transitions (Detected vs cutoff/deconditioned)

Use Cases:
- Infer which binary features contribute to an EDR’s process identity key
- Design experiments to isolate detection/identity signals beyond common hashes
- Time deconditioning attempts around cache cooldown/reset windows
- Validate whether rebuilds/metadata changes meaningfully affect detection linkage

Keywords:
deconditioning, process identification, PI cache, cooldown time, EDR, antivirus, detection pipeline, cutoff, known-bad, LsassReader, differential testing, binary variants, imphash, SSDeep, TLSH, static fingerprinting, cache reset, detection state